Thank you for the excellent discussion in the McNamara's hand portion of the May forum.<br><br>
I am sorry that guys like Kennedy, Johnson, Rostow,... are gone. These guys are the architects of the beginning of the &quot;American War&quot; on Viet Nam and deserved to witness the fruits of their labor. McNamara &amp; Kissinger are still with us and wisely keeping a low profile. <br><br>
I am opposed to the death penalty because it allows no room for realization and change, but I think these guys are war criminals and deserve to be called to the carpet for what they did. They had so much power and used it without realizing the consequences of that exercise of power. I think emptying bedpans in VA hospitals would be a good start. This could start a trend that might make leaders a little cautious about sending people off to kill one another. <br><br>
I am not down on the soldiers. I was one of them, just lucky enough that I didn't wade the paddies or hump the boonies but I would have killed my &quot;enemy&quot; before he got me if that would have been within my power. The point is that our leaders were supposed to be &quot;the best and the brightest&quot; and they either failed to see that our &quot;enemy&quot; was on his on turf where he rightfully belonged and we had no business being in Viet Nam at all or the powers-that-be in America were serving their own ends and didn't give a whit about the lives that were in the balance. Two guesses about my opinion.<br><br>
An inscription on the Viet Nam veteran's memorial here in Salt Lake City reads something to the effect: &quot;Woe to the statesman whose reasons for entering a war are not so clear at its end as at the beginning.&quot; NO SHIT!!! And on memorials we STILL allow them to carve into stone &quot;...gave their lives in the cause of freedom...&quot;. Whose freedom did we buy with all those lives?? The Vietnamese?? Ours?? I don't think so. Even my mother, bless her sweet, polite heart says &quot;We were sold a bill of goods&quot;.<br><br>
We need those memorials to say: &quot;...sacrificed by corporate and political greed...&quot;. We could start telling the truth right there.<br><br>
Lewis Downey<br>
